### ORCID

ORCID stands for Open Researcher and Contributer ID: A persistent digital identifier for anyone working in academia. 
ORCID is a unique personal number that allows researchers to easily and automatically connect their research information across a wide range of online databases. 
You can think of ORCID as the academic equivalent of your passport: It ensures other research systems and services know who you are and what you published and contributed.

## The benefits of ORCID

*Update your repositories instantly*

When you link your ORCID to an institutional CRIS, such as VU research portal, your research identity and work are immediately synchronized. 
This means that any new publication or achievement you add to your ORCID profile will seamlessly update across your chosen repositories. 
No more manual updates, your latest work is always showcased.

*Gain an institute-independent overview of your research achievements*

ORCID provides an universal identity that is not tied to any specific institution and offers you an independent overview of your research achievements that transcends organizational boundaries.
This is especially valuable when you move between institutions during your research career, as your ORCID remains consistent and regardless of where you work.

*Improve your visibility among peers, publishers and funders*

ORCID is globally recognized and widely adopted by institutions, publishers and funders. By linking your ORCID to VU Amsterdam, you become easily discoverable by your peers and collaborators. 
When you use your ORCID in submissions and research proposals, you ensure that your work is respected on a global scale. 

*Contribute effortlessly to open science*

ORCID is a non-profit organization driven by the scientific community. 
By taking control over your own research identity in an open system, you contribute to the ethos of open science by making research more accessible and transparent. 
The convenience of ORCID helps remove administrative barriers, allowing researchers to focus on their work and share their findings more readily.

